From Rare Earth Leverage to Layered Sovereignty: China’s Export Ban and the Reconfiguration of 21st-Century Geopolitics

On 6 January, China escalated its regulatory measures on dual-use technologies—covering rare earth elements, permanent magnets, and other critical minerals essential for advanced defense manufacturing—by converting existing export restrictions into a formalized export ban. This policy shift signals a transition from regulatory oversight to outright denial of supply in strategically sensitive sectors.

On Tuesday, 24 February, China’s Ministry of Commerce announced the suspension of shipments of so-called “dual-use” goods—materials applicable to both civilian and military domains—to 20 Japanese companies. An additional 20 entities were placed on a newly established “monitoring list.” The immediate export prohibition encompasses major industrial and defense-related actors, including Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, Kawasaki Heavy Industries, IHI Corporation, the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA), and Japan’s National Defense Academy. A further 20 organizations—including Subaru and Sumitomo Heavy Industries—were subjected to case-by-case export approvals under the monitoring mechanism.

Entities placed on the monitoring list will encounter slower shipment processes and will be required to formally commit that dual-use items will not contribute to the enhancement of Japan’s military capabilities. The timing of the announcement appears politically responsive. In November 2024, Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi publicly stated that a Chinese invasion of Taiwan could constitute an existential threat and that Tokyo might respond with armed force. China’s export controls can thus be interpreted not merely as commercial regulation but as calibrated geopolitical signaling.

Earlier in February, the Tokyo government announced the extraction of mineral-rich seabed sediment from approximately 6,000 meters beneath the ocean near Minamitorishima. While symbolically significant, this deep-sea mining trial remains far from commercial viability. The technological, environmental, and economic barriers to scalable exploitation are substantial.

Japan’s prior attempt to diversify its rare earth supply through development of the Dong Pao deposit in Vietnam’s Lai Chau province illustrates the fragility of alternative sourcing strategies. After China depressed global rare earth prices, Japanese investors withdrew from the project. Plans to revive operations in 2023 were further disrupted by the arrest of the local partner’s chairman. The episode underscores the structural difficulty of displacing China’s dominant position in rare earth markets.

In April 2025, China imposed export controls on seven heavy rare earth elements in response to U.S. tariffs, triggering significant global disruptions. Although these restrictions were not Japan-specific, Japanese automakers—including Nissan and Suzuki—reported supply chain interruptions. Suzuki temporarily suspended production of its Swift model, demonstrating the downstream industrial impact of upstream mineral constraints.

Since mid-2025, the United States has sought to mitigate strategic vulnerability by signing framework agreements or contracts on critical minerals with more than twenty countries, including Malaysia, Thailand, Indonesia, and Japan. These initiatives reflect an emerging competition to secure diversified supply chains for inputs central to high-technology and defense sectors.

Although control over critical minerals is not yet debated with the same intensity as oil, it is poised to become a foundational instrument of geopolitical leverage. The evolving contest over rare earths and associated technologies illustrates a broader structural transformation in international power dynamics.

This transformation can be conceptualized as the “Geopolitical Rupture of the 21st Century” and its doctrinal articulation: the Layered Sovereignty Model: Physical Power – Technological Capacity – Cognitive Legitimacy
The geopolitical reconfiguration of the 21st century is not merely a redistribution of material capabilities; it entails a redefinition of the nature of state power itself.

Classical geopolitics asked: Who controls territory?

The defining question of the present century is fundamentally different: Who processes the data, who manages the system, and who persuades the society?

This shift marks a transition from a territorially centered model of sovereignty toward a multilayered architecture of authority. The contemporary state can no longer be understood solely as a geographic entity; it functions as an operational socio-technological ecosystem.

